article.description:
Nicole Ohlde had career highs of 21 points and 11 rebounds to lead the
Minnesota Lynx past the Connecticut Sun 66-63 Wednesday.
article.headline: Ohlde: Career-highs in points, boards
article.linkText: Ohlde, but goodie: Lynx slip past Sun
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- This time, Nicole Ohlde got the best of
Lindsay Whalen.

Ohlde had career highs of 21 points and 11 rebounds to lead the
Minnesota Lynx past the Connecticut Sun 66-63 Wednesday.

Katie Smith added 15 points and hit a couple of crucial free
throws in the final minute to help the Lynx spoil the homecoming of
Whalen, the former University of Minnesota star who led the Golden
Gophers to the Final Four last season.

The last time she played in Minneapolis, Whalen led the Gophers
to a win over Ohlde's Kansas State Wildcats in the second round of
the NCAA tournament.

"That stuff's all in the past," Ohlde said when asked if the
college rivalry carried into the pros.

Whalen, still a hero in her home state, led the Sun with a
career-high 18 points and got a rousing ovation during
introductions. A Lynx-record crowd of 16,227 cheered every time
Whalen scored -- she finished 6-for-12.

But it wasn't enough to counter Ohlde, Smith and Tamika
Williams, who combined for 46 points.

"They've got a good team over there," Sun coach Mike Thibault
said. "They're going to contend for the Western Conference
title."

Ohlde, Minnesota's 6-foot-4 center who entered the game ranked
second among WNBA rookies with a 10.4-point scoring average, got
most of her points banging around inside. She also shot 9-for-14
from the line.

"Ohlde was going tonight and we kept going to her," Smith
said. "And she was making them pay."

It was the third double-double of Ohlde's career.

"Nicole Ohlde was phenomenal today," Lynx coach Suzie
McConnell Serio said.

The Sun, winners of seven of their last eight games, tied the
game at 60-all on Katie Douglas' two free throws with 1:02
remaining. But Smith hit a pair of foul shots with 37.9 seconds to
play, and Douglas missed a jumper on Connecticut's next possession.
Ohlde sank two more free throws with 18.2 left to make it 64-60.

Whalen capped her career day with three-point play on a no-look
shot underneath the basket with 3.8 seconds left that made it
64-63.

But Smith made two more free throws to seal the win for
Minnesota, which has won five of six.

"A few plays here or there, a few offensive rebounds in the
second half, and it could've been a different story," Whalen said.

Connecticut jumped to an early lead, but the Lynx took advantage
of Connecticut's poor shooting and crept back into the game.
Minnesota closed out the first half with a 12-7 run to take a 34-30
halftime lead.
